# Type Compatibility for Widely Used Types

## Context
- Applies to all TypeScript files within the project
- Ensures that changes to widely used types do not introduce breaking changes

## Requirements
- When modifying types that are widely used (e.g., HTML Rules, API Interceptors), ensure that the changes are backward compatible
- Before making changes to such types, identify all usages across the codebase to assess the impact
- Use TypeScript's structural typing to maintain compatibility; avoid removing or altering existing properties unless necessary
- If a breaking change is unavoidable, document the change thoroughly and update all affected areas accordingly
- Prefer extending existing types over modifying them directly to preserve compatibility

## Examples
- Good:
  ```typescript
    interface proxifiedObjGeneratorContext {
        specialInterceptionFeatures?: InterceptionFeaturesEnum;
        overwriteRecords?: overwriteRecordsType;
    }
  ```
- Bad:
  ```typescript
    interface proxifiedObjGeneratorContext {
        specialInterceptionFeatures?: InterceptionFeaturesEnum;
    }
  ```